{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6f5fadba-c192-4d43-baec-eb1a1e873a0c","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, the OS automatically generates a **`.ips` crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nor the system-wide location:\n\n```\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`. You can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them.\n\nSince NativeAOT doesn't ship `createdump`, these OS-generated `.ips` files are your primary crash artifact. They contain the native backtrace, signal info, and thread state. You can symbolicate the .NET runtime frames using the `apple-crash-symbolication` skill if needed — just say the word.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"56615979-4caf-44bb-a3f2-5dd7ff35c859","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without createdump. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":271,"requestId":"CB09:3454B1:21D94EC:251EE85:6A052982"},"id":"586716d2-5633-4ada-bb51-f9f0fcd284d8","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:46:51.286Z","parentId":"020baf59-e6c4-4ab1-af81-e57aa28cbf26"}
